<br>
It's too bad that the author of that piece had to focus on the Knights and draw parallels with the Klan.  Those types of strawmen/ad hominems usually end up limiting the power of an argument due to the crass way they had to criticize the opposing arguments.  Although the idea may have been floated by the Knights of Columbus, the actual initiate in Congress and by Eisenhower was directed more to drawing a distinction between the USSR (&quot;Godless Communists&quot;) than anything to endorse a particular religion.<br>
<br>
Procedural note for those that don't know how the judiciary works:  This three judge panels decision is not final for 45 days, during which a party can appeal to higher court, and then the ruling is held in abeyance while the higher court rules.  In this case, it would be an En Banc hearing by a dozen or so judges from the 9th Circuit.  <br>
<br>
The three judges were split 2-1, and an En Banc panel is likely to reject their interpretation on several grounds.  First, jurisdictionally.  The complaint by the atheist dad was that his daughter was forced to hear the Pledge, and that this was damaging.  However, the Supreme Court has ruled on several occasions, that merely hearing or seeing something is not sufficient damage (except for minors seeing abusive/offensive material).  The Pledge won't fall within such an exception, and the three judges didn't argue it did, so the court should have rejected the appeal on those grounds.  En Banc or the Supremes certainly will.<br>
<br>
Second, the Supreme Court just ruled today that school vouchers are okay, even if some of the money goes to religious schools.  Such a ruling would seem to fly in the face of the Pledge Ruling.<br>
<br>
Third, it's simply counter to the past ruling of the Supreme Court.  The Court starts out its sessions with something along the lines of &quot;God save this honourable Court....&quot;  So does Congress.  Both have been challenged numerous times, and lost.  The Declaration of Independence, which the author of the ACLU piece shockingly quoted some other part <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  , states that &quot;all men are endowed by their Creator....&quot;  Kinda hard to say that their intent was to remove religion from all vestiges of public life.  And then there is &quot;In God We Trust,&quot; which has been on our money a heck of a lot longer than anything going back 50 years and the Cold War.<br>
<br>
Finally, IMHO, it simply is not contrary to the First Amendment.  The Amendment guarantees Freedom <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> OF</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Religion, not Freedom <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> FROM</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Religion.  The Appellant and his daughter were perfectly capable of believing whatever they chose.  [I wonder if the guy will let his daughter go to church if she wanted?]  Hearing the Pledge is not requiring obedience or belief.  Two different animals.<br>
